Jonathan Ginzburg
-------------

   Last Call for Papers:

  LONDIAL: 2008 WORKSHOP ON THE SEMANTICS AND PRAGMATICS OF DIALOGUE

  King=92s College London, June 2nd =96 June 4th, 2008

  in conjunction with:

  Final workshop of Dialogue Matters: Foundations for Technology =20
Development

(Leverhulme International Network Project).  This workshop is now to =20
be held with the first day at King=92s College London on June 2nd =20
immediately preceding LONDIAL, the second day at Queen Mary, =20
University of London (QMUL) on June 5th (NOTE: change of dates of =20
this workshop).

                                               (Apologies for =20
Multiple Postings)

  The SEMDIAL series of workshops aim to bring together researchers =20
working on the semantics and pragmatics of dialogue in fields such as =20=

artificial intelligence, computational linguistics, formal semantics/=20
pragmatics, philosophy, psychology, and neural science. In 2008 we =20
will celebrate eleven years of the SEMDIAL series with the LONDIAL =20
workshop, to be organized at King=92s College London (KCL) in =20
conjunction with the Interaction, Media and Communication Group at =20
Queen Mary, University of London (QMUL). The SEMDIAL workshops are =20
always stimulating and fun, and with KCL being in the heart of =20
London, just across from the South Bank Centre, there will be no =20
shortage of evening entertainment.



LONDIAL 2008 will be held in conjunction with the closing workshop of =20=

the Leverhulme-funded network Dialogue Matters: Foundations for =20
Technology Development, initially set up between London (KCL, QMUL), =20
Edinburgh/Glasgow, Stanford, Stony Brook, Gothenburg, Essex, with =20
additional collaborators now also participating. This two-day =20
workshop will feature invited presentations by members of this group =20
and other leaders of the computational linguistics and human language =20=

technology community, and demonstration of the Augmented Human =20
Interaction Laboratory at QMUL (June 5th). This series of workshops =20
has provided an extremely fruitful synergy of theoretical, =20
historical, computational and psycho-linguists, with overlapping =20
interests in dialogue modeling. Confirmed speakers include Susan =20
Brennan, Amanda Stent, Robin Cooper, Staffan Larsson, Stanley Peters, =20=

and Holly Branigan.



There is also a planned session on dialogue situated in joint action.



DATES AND DEADLINES:



Submissions due: 21st March 2008

(Please specify if you are submitting to the DSiJA or not)

Notification: 16th April 2008

Final version due: 30th April 2008

Dialogue Matters opening workshop: 2nd June 2008 (Monday)

LONDIAL 2008: 2nd =96 4th June 2008 (Monday - Wednesday)

Dialogue Matters workshop meeting at QMUL:  5th June 2008 (Thursday)



SCOPE (expanded from first call):



We invite papers on all topics related to the semantics and =20
pragmatics of dialogues, including, but not limited to:

- models of common ground/mutual belief in communication

- modeling agents' information states and how they get updated

- multi-agent models and turn-taking

- goals, intentions and commitments in communication

- semantic interpretation in dialogue

- reference in dialogue

- ellipsis resolution in dialogue

- alignment and misalignment in dialogue

- dialogue and discourse structure

- dialogue situated in joint action

- interpretation of questions and answers

- incremental, context-dependent processing

- nonlinguistic interaction in communication

- natural language understanding and reasoning in spoken dialogue =20
systems

- multimodal dialogue systems

- dialogue management in practical implementations

- categorization of dialogue moves or speech acts in corpora

- designing and evaluating dialogue systems



There is also a planned session on dialogue situated in joint action =20
(DSiJA). Submissions of papers are invited for this session.



SUBMISSION:



Deadline for receipt of papers is 21st March 2008, 23:59 UTC.

Submit your paper via the web at

  http://www.easychair.org/conferences/?conf=3Dlondial2008

  Before submitting you must register with the website and receive a =20
password by email; please do this well ahead of your submission, =20
since email is sometimes unreliable. You will also need to fill out a =20=

web form with the author details and type in (or paste) a plain-text =20
version of your abstract (200 words), in addition to uploading your =20
paper.



The actual paper should be an anonymous PDF file, 8 pages long =20
(including data, tables, figures, and references), A4 paper size, =20
11pt Times font, 2.5 cm (1 inch) margins, 2-column format. Include a =20
one-paragraph abstract of the entire work (about 200 words). You may =20
find it convenient to use the style files provided by ACL 2007. =20
Please specify whether your paper is for the DSiJA.

Multiple submissions by the same author or group of authors are =20
allowed, but each person may only give one oral presentation at the =20
workshop.



We will have a separate submission of late-breaking system =20
demonstrations and ongoing project descriptions, to be presented in a =20=

poster session during the workshop. Late-breaking submissions will be =20=

two pages long; they will not be refereed, but evaluated for =20
relevance only by the program committee chairs. Submission of late-=20
breaking abstracts will be allowed only after review of the main =20
session papers has concluded. The deadline for late-breaking =20
submissions is 30th April 2008.



INVITED SPEAKERS:



David Traum, University of Southern California

Andrzej Wisniewski, Adam Mickiewicz University

Susan Fussell, Carnegie Mellon University

(one more to be confirmed)



PROCEEDINGS:



Final, 8-page versions of the accepted papers, together with the 2-=20
page accepted late-breaking abstracts, will be distributed in a =20
proceedings volume at the workshop. In order to ensure publication in =20=

the proceedings, AT LEAST ONE author of each paper must have =20
registered to attend the meeting by 30th April 2008, the deadline of =20
submission of the revised paper.



ORGANIZATION:



Pat Healey (program co-chair)

Jonathan Ginzburg (program co-chair)

Ruth Kempson, Miriam Bouzouita, Eleni Gregoromichelaki (local =20
arrangements)



